meta: | theme: editorial | type: newsletter | issue: 47 | date: 2026-06-24

title: The Doha Design Review
byline: Curated by Noor Al-Thani · Monthly dispatch on architecture, culture, and the built environment

dedication: For everyone who believes good design is a public good.

epigraph: "Architecture is the thoughtful making of space." — Louis Kahn

section: Lead Story
figure: National Museum of Qatar at dusk | src: https://cdn.dohadesign.qa/nmoq-dusk-2026.jpg | caption: The desert rose blooms at golden hour. Jean Nouvel's masterpiece continues to define the city's architectural identity.

text: This month we explore how Qatar's built environment is evolving beyond the landmark projects of the 2010s. The focus has shifted to human-scale interventions: pedestrian zones, adaptive reuse, and climate-responsive neighbourhoods.

section: In This Issue
- The Msheireb model: 10 years on
- Cooling the public realm: lessons from Msheireb and Lusail
- Interview: Mariam Al-Homaid on public space

section: The Msheireb Model
text: A decade after its inauguration, Msheireb Downtown Doha remains the benchmark for walkable, mixed-use development in the Gulf. But replicating its success elsewhere requires more than copying the facade treatments.

quote: "The magic was in the master plan — the density, the shading, the way streets breathe." — Mariam Al-Homaid, Chief Architect, Msheireb Properties

figure: Shaded walkway in Msheireb | src: https://cdn.dohadesign.qa/msheireb-walkway.jpg | caption: Mashtrabiya screens reduce solar gain by 40%.

section: Cooling the Public Realm
text: With summer temperatures routinely exceeding 45°C, outdoor comfort is not a luxury but a necessity. Lusail's new waterfront promenade deploys a toolkit of passive and active cooling strategies.

footnote: All temperature data sourced from Qatar Meteorology Department, 2025 annual report.

section: Interview
text: We spoke with Mariam Al-Homaid about the next chapter for public space in Qatar.

quote: "The question is no longer 'can we build it?' but 'should we build it, and for whom?'" — Mariam Al-Homaid

section: Coming Next Month
text: A deep dive into the Lusail Stadium legacy conversion and what it means for community sports infrastructure.

caption: Cover image: National Museum of Qatar, photographed by Ali Al-Naimi, 2026.